HEADWORD: Strategical
<hw>Stra*te"gic*al</hw>,
}</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ of or for a general: cf. F.
<ets>strat⟦eacute⟧gique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to strategy;
effected by artifice.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Stra*te"gic*al*ly</wf>,
<pos>adv.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Strategic line</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a line
joining strategic points.</cd> -- <col><b>Strategic point</b></col>
<fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>any point or region in the theater or warlike
operations which affords to its possessor an advantage over his
opponent, as a mountain pass, a junction of rivers or roads, a fortress,
etc.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

